node.text:
There is power in your voice, in your vote, in who you are. Refuse to be suppressed.🗣️

📅 On this day in 1965, President Johnson signed the Voting Rights Act into law, outlawing poll taxes, literacy tests, and other practices that effectively prevented southern Black people from voting. It was nearly 100 years after African American men received the right to vote with the ratification of the 15th Amendment.

📺 Upon signing the act into law, President Johnson said in a nationwide address, "every American citizen must have an equal right to vote. There is no reason which can excuse the denial of that right. There is no duty which weighs more heavily on us than the duty we have to ensure that right."

🗳️ Voting is power. And it's just as relevant today. We love this quote by @lizzobeeating from her Grammy award acceptance speech in 2020: “When people try to suppress something, it's normally because that thing holds power. They're afraid of your power. There's power in who you are, there's power in your voice. Whether it's through music, through protest, or your right to vote, use your power, use your voice, and refuse to be suppressed.”

🔗 Learn more about the Voting Rights Act on Khan Academy at the link in our bio. 🔗

📷Photo of Lizzo by Andy Witchger.
